xt-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Proper governa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nce, by way of screening and auditing, is required to ensure the scheme is effective.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Medical experts should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">have a certain level of clinical experience and a working knowledge of up to date recognised research in the relevant med</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ical area. </span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In terms of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">reporting, the expert should receive both the claimant’s and defendant’s account of the accident. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is not however, necessary for experts to see medical records in all cases, nor should it be a pre-requisite for claimants to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> attend upon a medical practiti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">oner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> after an accident.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A standard form report is not required although the inclusion within the examination of agreed objective testing in all cases would be beneficial.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Fixed fees should be introduced to ensure consistency, reduce costs generally and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">reduce the potential for disagreement.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The reforms should be implemented at the earliest opportunity.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Other issues for possible consideration include a review of the level of damages for pain, suffering and loss of amenity (PSLA) in whiplash claims and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> extension of the ban on inducements to law firms.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Committee is also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">encouraged</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to support the inclusion of fraud in personal injury claims within the Law Commission’s 12</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> programme of reform.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">accreditation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">scheme </span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The government has touched u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">pon the need for proper governance of the scheme and we would welcome more information as to how the scheme would be run.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">For the scheme to have credibility, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e believe it is essential that panel appointees are properly screened, that there is a method for auditing and checking reports and that experts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> do not meet the necessary standards lose accreditation. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">So as to ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">reporting process is as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">resilient and as fair as possible, we take the view that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">all accredited experts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> should be trained in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> biomechanics of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> injury and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> be provided with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the latest research on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> vehicle safety </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">from bodies such as the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Thatcham Research Centre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  Our view is that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">here is currently a lack of real </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in this area and that experts are often unawar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">vehicle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> features and how they</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">work in the event of an accident.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">To assist the expert in arriving at a considered view, the expert should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">furnished</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the claimant’s and the defendant’s account of the accident.  This would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ensure that the expert receives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a balanced view as to how the accident was said to have taken place</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, the speeds involved and directions of travel.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We do not believe that it is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> necess</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ary for expert</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> access to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> medical records in all cases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. To introduce such a rule would simply increase costs and lengthen the amount of time taken to produce reports.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> are of the view</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the option should be available to defendants to obtain m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">edical records</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> where</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e prognosis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">period </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">exceed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 9 months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the cost of obtaining those records should be at the defendant’s expense.  This would enable defendants to consider causation in more detail and rule out the possibility that other factors are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in play, such as a pre-existing medical condition, fraud or exaggeration.  Where an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> expert felt that it was absolutely necessary to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> have access to medical records</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> properly complete </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, then </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> expert</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ould communicate that to the parties and e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">xplain the reasons why</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  The claimant and/or the defendant could then decide whether to make the records available in that case.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> do not feel that it should be a prerequisite for clai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">mants to visit their GP or an A&amp;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">E department after an accident </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tablish a record of the injury </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">so as to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">be able to </sp